### Before reporting an issue

- [X] I have read and understood the above terms for submitting issues, and I understand that my issue may be closed without action if I do not follow them.

### Area

authorization-services

### Describe the bug

[RFC 8693](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8693) security section suggests hardening of token exchange flows using scopes:

> In addition, both delegation and impersonation introduce unique security issues. Any time one principal is delegated the rights of another principal, the potential for abuse is a concern. The use of the scope claim (in addition to other typical constraints such as a limited token lifetime) is suggested to mitigate potential for such abuse, as it restricts the contexts in which the delegated rights can be exercised.

So I've tried setting it up using `source` and `target` client ids.
1. Created a new client scope named `token-exchange` and added a hardcoded claim mapper that adds it to the access token as `"token-exchange":true`.
2. Created a _client scope_ policy in the `realm-management` client, which requires a `token-exchange` scope
3. Added the scope to the `source` client scopes
4.  Created a permission on the `target` client to allow token-exchange with the policy from step 2.

Then, I request a new access token from the `source` client:
```bash
curl --location 'https://staging/realms/master/protocol/openid-connect/token' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded' \
--data-urlencode 'client_id=source' \
--data-urlencode 'client_secret=[REDACTED]' \
--data-urlencode 'grant_type=client_credentials' \
--data-urlencode 'scope=token-exchange'
```
And when I attempt to exchange it I get `500 Internal Server Error`.
```bash
curl --location 'https://staging/realms/master/protocol/openid-connect/token' \
--header 'Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded' \
--data-urlencode 'client_id=source' \
--data-urlencode 'client_secret=[REDACTED]' \
--data-urlencode 'subject_token=TOKEN' \
--data-urlencode 'audience=target' \
--data-urlencode 'grant_type=urn:ietf:params:oauth:grant-type:token-exchange' \
--data-urlencode 'requested_token_type=urn:ietf:params:oauth:token-type:access_token'
```


### Version

22.0.3

### Expected behavior

Client scope policy works

